Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – In the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden shifts in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely, because when emerging from the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many ways, particularly in terms of sovereign debts and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are at the root of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
In the first place, they are not easy to detect with certainty and even more difficult to prove.
Then, predicting the exact moment of the breakdown (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed, and when there is no credit available) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without warning signs.
Periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those who are least responsible.
If this pattern were to repeat, it could erode confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could signal excessive regulation, state intervention, and disengagement from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a sovereign debt crisis for advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can translate into a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration of tax revenues and an increase in bailout spending.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of advanced economies' "fiscal packages" include non-discretionary countercyclical measures.
The imbalances and undetected systemic risks make what appear to be prudent fiscal policies actually ineffective.
Spain, for example, had no fiscal deficit at the start of the crisis.
But its revenues and expenditures were largely determined by a housing bubble linked to very high levels of debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is undoubtedly a prime example.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can trigger this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, sovereign states must be vigilant about the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk, and able to take rapid corrective measures.
New detailed legislative frameworks, emphasizing capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings, and other information sources, incentives, conflicts of interest, and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms will soon be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will in no way solve the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and signaling instability.
In addition to and complementing new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
However, some leading politicians and analysts believe that such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, is futile.
Incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex, constantly evolving global financial system make it, according to them, either impossible or so error-prone that such an effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are correct, we must then accept that we will periodically find ourselves in a situation of financial and fiscal instability that cannot be predicted in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than the one we deemed necessary just three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one is to reject a true proposition and the other is to accept a false proposition.
Call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be framed as follows: in the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors is likely to have the highest cost?
The opponents of prudent systemic risk monitoring hold two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable precursor indicating an increasing potential instability.
Looking for such a sign is a waste of time.
The instability occurs instantly.
But this position seems fallacious.
During the 2008 crisis, for example, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note.
It must be admitted, however, that these warnings were perhaps not sufficient to be irrefutable, and they certainly did not anticipate the tipping point.
They were nonetheless undeniable signals.
The second position is that there are indeed precursors, but they are so unreliable that taking action would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that the cost of AQF is likely higher than RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or the remedy is worse than the problem.
There are undoubtedly costs associated with the AQF error.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so the negative aggregate effect of reacting to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced.
There might be a deeper tendency at play.
Whether in business or investments, choices are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty and errors are frequent.
The default position of advanced countries' decision-makers seems to be, on the contrary, that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply ingrained belief that financial markets are stable and regulate themselves.
If one believes that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refrain from acting unless there are good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at least questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop, and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try this experience, and in doing so, give responsibilities to a new institution, or an existing one, that has access to relevant information, possesses sharp analytical skills both at the financial and macroeconomic levels, and is relatively insulated from conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence perceptions of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby enhancing the system's ability to regulate itself.
